Hasini Jayatilaka is postdoctoral fellow at Stanford University focused on elucidating mechanisms that govern relapse in childhood cancers, particularly B-cell precursor acute lymphoblastic leukemia (BCP-ALL) and neuroblastoma.

BCP-ALL is a common childhood malignancy that has seen dramatic improvements in survival using current treatment regimens. However, relapse is the most frequent cause of cancer-related death among children with BCP-ALL. Jayatilaka is studying the activation of pro-survival and drug resistance mechanisms in a subset of the BCP-ALL population that allow tumor cells to persist following treatment and cause relapse.

Jayatilaka is currently conducting research on understanding the complex pathways that govern metastasis, the spread of cancer, which is responsible for 90% of cancer related deaths. She recently discovered a new signaling pathway that controls metastasis and showed that by blocking the pathway, the spread of cancer can be slowed down.

Jayatilaka grew up in Sri Lanka and pursued her BS and PhD in Chemical and Bimolecular Engineering at Johns Hopkins University.

author: Hasini_Jayatilaka;
title: How cancer cells communicate -- and how we can slow them down

aws-transcripts.transcript: cancer. It's a devastating disease that takes an enormous emotional tool not only on the patient, but the patients loved ones as well. It is a battle that the human race has been fighting for centuries, and while we've made some advancements, we still haven't beaten it. Two out of five people in the U. S will develop cancer in their lifetime. Off those, 90% was to come to the disease due to metastases. Metastases is a spread of cancer from a primary site toe, a distal site through the circulatory or the lymphatic system. For instance, a female patient with breast cancer doesn't succumb to the disease simply because she has a moss on her breast. She succumbs the disease because it spreads to the lungs, liver, lymph nodes, brain born where it becomes a NRA, SEPTA ble or untreatable Metastases is a complicated process, one that I've studied for several years now, and something that my team and I discovered recently was that cancer cells are able to communicate with each other and coordinate their movement based on how closely packed there in the tumor micro environment, they communicate with each other through to signalling molecules called interleukin six and interleukin eight. Now, like anything else in nature, when things get a little too tight, this signal is enhanced, causing the cancer cells to move away faster from the primary site and spread to a new site. So if we block the signal using a drug cocktail that we developed, we can stop the communication between cancer cells and slow down the spread of cancer. Let me pause here for a second and take you back to when this all began for me in 2010 when I was just a sophomore in college. I had just started working in Dr Denny Worth's lab at Johns Hopkins University, and I'll be honest. I was a young, naive SriLankan Go, who had no previous research experience, and I was asked to look at how cancer cells move in a three d college in one matrix that recapture elated in a dish the conditions that cancer cells are exposed to in our bodies.
